  "prompt": "Graph Theory: What does it mean if vertices are adjacent?",
  "response": "In graph theory, two vertices are considered adjacent (or neighboring) if they are directly connected by an edge in the graph.\n\nMore specifically:\n- If there is a direct edge between vertex A and vertex B\n- The vertices are said to be adjacent to each other\n- They have a direct connection without going through any other vertices\n\nFor example, in a graph where vertices represent cities and edges represent roads:\n- If there's a road directly connecting New York and Boston, those city vertices are adjacent\n- If you must go through another city to reach a destination, those vertices are NOT adjacent\n\nKey points:\n- Adjacency is a fundamental concept in graph theory\n- It defines the direct connections between vertices\n- In an undirected graph, adjacency is symmetrical (if A is adjacent to B, then B is adjacent to A)\n- In a directed graph, adjacency can be one-way\n\nExample:\nA --- B means A and B are adjacent vertices\nA \u2192 B means A and B are adjacent in a directed graph, but not necessarily B to A",
